Targeting Model: Statics on R and $\delta$ (easygoing agent)¶

James Yu, 17 January 2022

In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
In [2]:
def strategy(T, R, delta = 1):
    A = np.array([
      [0.99, 0.01], # stubborn agent, self-loop = 0.99
      [0.5 * 0.99, 0.5 * 0.99], # easily-influenced agent
    ], ndmin = 2)

    B = np.array([
      [0],                     
      [0.01] # target the easygoing agent
    ], ndmin = 2)

    Q = 1 * np.identity(2) # the Q from the original notebook here
    
    x = np.array([
    [4],
    [4]
    ], ndmin = 2)

    K_t = [Q]
    K = Q
    for i in range(T):
        K = delta * (A.T @ (K - (K @ B @ np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K)) @ A) + Q
        K_t.insert(0, K)
  
    x_t = x
    r_ts = []
    payoff = 0
    payoffs = []
    x_ts = [x]
    i = 0
    for K in K_t[1:]:
        r_t = -(np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K @ A) @ x_t # myopic strategy
        r_ts.append(r_t)
        payoff += (-1 * delta**i * (x_t.T @ Q @ x_t)).item() + (-1 * delta**i * (R * r_t**2)).item()
        payoffs.append(payoff)
        x_t_new = A @ x_t + B @ r_t
        x_ts.append(x_t_new)
        x_t = x_t_new
        i += 1
    
    return K_t, r_ts, x_ts, payoffs

$\delta = 0$, $R$ variable¶

Where results are rounded, $0.0$ is not 0.

In [3]:
K_ts, messages, opinions, payoffs = strategy(30, 0)
plt.plot(range(len(messages)), [m.item() for m in messages])
plt.title("Message vs Time: R = 0")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Message")
plt.show()
In [4]:
for R in np.linspace(0.001, 0.1, 10):
    K_ts, messages, opinions, payoffs = strategy(30, R)
    plt.plot(range(len(messages)), [m.item() for m in messages], label = "R = "+str(round(R, 2)))
plt.title("Message vs Time")
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Message")
plt.show()

In [7]:
K_ts, messages, opinions, payoffs = strategy(30, 0)
agent_0 = [x[0].item() for x in opinions]
agent_1 = [x[1].item() for x in opinions]
plt.plot(range(len(agent_0)), agent_0, label = "Stubborn Agent")
plt.plot(range(len(agent_1)), agent_1, label = "Easily-Influenced Agent")
plt.title("Opinions vs Time: R = 0")
plt.xlabel("Time")
plt.ylabel("Agent Opinions")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

R = 0, $\delta$ variable¶

Note the $\delta = 1, R = 0$ base case is already given above.

plt.legend()
